@mkcor I think it is?

https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0008/#indentation

> The closing brace/bracket/parenthesis on multiline constructs may either line up under the first non-whitespace character of the last line of list [...] or it may be lined up under the first character of the line that starts the multiline construct

> Explaining the context for why code exists is important, especially maintaining code over the long term. I like to encode the decision and reasoning behind different actions in the code.

I do understand the importance of using comments to explain context where it cannot be explained easily via variable or function naming. And I recognize that everyone has a different preference as to their level of documentation via comments. :) To be more specific in my original comment, comments like this strike me as redundant and make the code more cluttered.

```<Button
     className={`btn ${
         // Only make this primary if there is no profiler link.
                  profilerLink
                    ? 'btn-outline-darker-secondary'
                    : 'btn-darker-secondary' (was  `primary` in previous commit)
                } btn-sm`}
```

So it was a nit, to be sure, but also a poorly worded request to please omit comments like this and only include comments that are truly necessary for context. :)

