Hmm I feel like this stack of context -> memo -> fake hook function -> state is quite a lot to grok. (eg: what exactly re-renders when this useState is altered? I think it's the react component invoking this function, but the component must call it on EVERY render or React will throw an exception because of a "conditional" `useState`?) 

It looks structurally sound though and is pretty cool! It's elegant hiding all the mess inside this context provider. I'd worry a bit about having to re-read this to make changes / fix bugs, but it seems unlikely we'll have to do much maintenance of a behavior like this 👍 

It is also tempting to fall back to a non-React solution here though. I think this could be implemented with a few imperative methods like this, where each new mouse enter removes any other hover state, and it's just tweaking class lists after the react render... (since it'd kinda be ok for the hover state to clear when the config editor content changes, anyway.)

```
onMouseEnter={e => {
   e.currentTarget.closest('.container').querySelector('.hovering')?.classList.remove('hovering')
   e.currentTarget.classList.add('hovering')
}
onMouseLeave={e => {
   e.currentTarget.classList.remove('hovering')
}
```

